nd reporters ever get the opportunity to do. The articles she includes touch on major themes that animated Dillon’s writing: downtown redevelopment, suburban sprawl, arts and culture, historic preservation, and the necessity of aesthetic quality in architecture as a baseline for thriving communities. While the specifics of these articles will resonate with those who care about Dallas, Fort Worth, and other Texas cities, they are also deeply relevant to all architects, urbanists, and citizens who engage in the public life and planning of cities. As a collection, The Open-Ended City persuasively demonstrates how a discerning critic helped to shape a landmark city by shaping the conversation about its architecture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchitecturezTexaszDallasxHistoryy20th century. 0aArchitecturezTexaszDallasxHistory. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh1 aDecherd, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDecherd, Robert.1 aFox, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolliday, Kathryn E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31761740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477318621423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477318621/original  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK